"# Chapter 9 — Registers, counters, and the birth of state

One D flip-flop stores one bit. Line up eight of them and you get an
8-bit register — a place to keep a byte between clock ticks. Wire the
output of a register through an adder and back into the register's
input, and you get a **counter** that increments every clock. Now you
have a machine that not only remembers, but remembers **something
that changes on purpose.**

This is the moment computing gets a **timeline.** Combinational logic
lives in a single frozen instant. Sequential logic — flip-flops plus
combinational logic plus a clock — lives across ticks. Before-and-after
becomes real.

## An 8-bit register

Eight D flip-flops, all sharing the same clock:

```
             CLK ---+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+
                    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |
                    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v
   D0 ------------> [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF]
   D1 ------------->
   ...
   D7 ---------------------------------->
                    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |
                    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v
                    Q0   Q1   Q2   Q3   Q4   Q5   Q6   Q7
```

Give the register eight data bits and pulse the clock. It samples them
all simultaneously and holds them until the next clock pulse. That is a
one-byte storage cell.

In Scheme, since we already have `make-d-flip-flop` from chapter 8, we
can chain eight:

```
(define (make-register width)
  (let ((flops (map (lambda (_) (make-d-flip-flop))
                    (iota width))))
    (lambda (msg . args)
      (cond
        ((eq? msg 'load)
         ;; args: (list of bits)
         (for-each (lambda (ff b) (ff 'set-d b)) flops (car args))
         'loaded)
        ((eq? msg 'tick)
         (for-each (lambda (ff) (ff 'tick)) flops)
         'ticked)
        ((eq? msg 'read)
         (map (lambda (ff) (ff 'q)) flops))))))

(define R (make-register 8))
(R 'load (list #t #f #t #f #f #f #f #f))   ;; low bit first: 5
(R 'tick)
(R 'read)   ;; => (#t #f #t #f #f #f #f #f)
```

That is an 8-bit register. Every CPU has a bunch of these. The 6502
had A, X, and Y (each 8-bit). The 80386 had EAX, EBX, ECX, EDX, ESI,
EDI (each 32-bit). A modern ARM has R0 through R30 (each 64-bit). All
the same shape as our little Scheme register.

## The program counter

There is one register in every CPU that has a special name: the
**program counter** (PC). It holds the address of the next instruction
to fetch. Every instruction cycle, the PC gets incremented. When there
is a jump or branch, the PC gets overwritten.

The PC is a register plus an adder plus a mux. When the CPU is
executing normally, the PC = PC + 1 each cycle. When the CPU jumps,
the PC = target address instead.

That is a **counter with a load input.** Which brings us to counters.

## A 4-bit ripple counter

The simplest counter is a chain of toggle flip-flops. On every clock
edge, bit 0 flips. Whenever bit 0 falls from 1 to 0, bit 1 flips.
Whenever bit 1 falls from 1 to 0, bit 2 flips. And so on.

Counts: 0000, 0001, 0010, 0011, 0100, 0101, ..., 1111, then wraps
back to 0000. Four bits gives you sixteen states.

**ASCII diagram of a 4-bit ripple counter:**

```
   CLK --->[T]--- Q0 ---+--->[T]--- Q1 ---+--->[T]--- Q2 ---+--->[T]--- Q3
           |            |    |            |    |            |    |
           |            +----+ (Q0 acts   +----+ (Q1 acts   +----+ (Q2 acts
           |                    as clock       as clock       as clock
           +------ ...           for [T]1)      for [T]2)      for [T]3)
```

Each T flip-flop toggles on the falling edge of its clock. The first
one's clock is the system clock. The next one's clock is the previous
one's output. Cascading.

In Motoi Scheme, let us just implement it as a plain counter register
(we don't need to fake toggle-flip-flops if we have modulo):

```
(define (make-counter width)
  (let ((count 0)
        (max   (expt 2 width)))
    (lambda (msg)
      (cond
        ((eq? msg 'tick)
         (set! count (modulo (+ count 1) max))
         count)
        ((eq? msg 'read) count)
        ((eq? msg 'reset) (set! count 0) count)))))

(define c (make-counter 4))
(c 'tick)   ;; => 1
(c 'tick)   ;; => 2
(c 'tick)   ;; => 3
(c 'tick)   ;; => 4
;; ...
(let loop ((i 0)) (if (< i 15) (begin (c 'tick) (loop (+ i 1)))))
(c 'read)   ;; => 3   ;; wrapped: 4 + 15 = 19, mod 16 = 3
```

Every tick, up by one. Wraps at 16. That is a 4-bit counter.

If you want a wide range of values without wrapping, just use a wider
counter. A 32-bit counter can count to 4 billion before wrapping. That
is enough for most program counters.

## Watch the loop

The counter is our first honest software loop. Every tick, we
increment. Same as a hardware counter, every clock edge, it
increments. Same as a `for` loop:

```
(let loop ((i 0))
  (if (< i 10)
      (begin
        (display i) (newline)
        (loop (+ i 1)))))
```

`i` is a counter. Each recursion is a clock tick. Each `+ 1` is an
adder. When the loop exits, `i` holds a specific value.

Every `for` loop you have ever written is a counter driving a piece of
work. In hardware, the counter is a chain of T flip-flops. In software,
the counter is an integer variable in a register that increments each
iteration. Same shape.

## The birth of state

State is what makes computers useful. A stateless computer would give
you the same output every time. Boring. A stateful computer remembers
what happened, changes based on it, and produces new behaviour.

Every computer is a big pile of state — registers, cache lines, RAM
pages, disk sectors, network buffers, GPU frame buffers — being
transformed by combinational logic between clock edges. That is the
whole game.

Sequential logic = combinational logic + memory + a clock. Every
higher structure — CPU, GPU, operating system, database, game,
compiler, LLM — is a sequential-logic machine at heart, wrapped in
enough abstraction that you can forget about the clock.

## Registers vs. RAM

Registers and RAM are both memory. The difference is speed and cost.

- **Register:** ~1 ns access, ~10 to 100 registers in a CPU, made of
  flip-flops or SRAM cells with dedicated wiring. Extremely fast because
  they are right next to the ALU.
- **SRAM (cache):** ~1 to 10 ns access, ~megabytes total, made of
  six-transistor cells. Fast, but has to go through address decoding.
- **DRAM (main memory):** ~100 ns access, ~gigabytes, made of
  one-transistor + one-capacitor cells. Cheap, dense, slow. Needs
  refreshing.
- **SSD:** ~microseconds access, ~terabytes, made of flash memory
  cells. Non-volatile.
- **Disk:** ~10 ms access, ~terabytes to petabytes, spinning platters.
  Cheap, huge, slow.

Ratios in speed: a modern register access is about a million times
faster than a disk access. Chapter 13 explains why this matters and
what programmers do about it.

## Modeling a small register file

Real CPUs have a **register file** — a small memory that holds a
handful of registers, addressed by number. Let us model one.

```
(define (make-register-file count width)
  (let ((registers (map (lambda (_) (make-register width))
                        (iota count))))
    (lambda (msg . args)
      (cond
        ((eq? msg 'write)   ;; args: idx bits
         (let ((idx  (car args))
               (bits (cadr args)))
           ((list-ref registers idx) 'load bits)
           ((list-ref registers idx) 'tick)
           'wrote))
        ((eq? msg 'read)    ;; args: idx
         ((list-ref registers (car args)) 'read))))))

(define rf (make-register-file 4 8))
(rf 'write 0 (list #t #f #t #f #f #f #f #f))    ;; R0 = 5
(rf 'write 1 (list #t #t #t #f #f #f #f #f))    ;; R1 = 7
(rf 'read 0)   ;; => (#t #f #t #f #f #f #f #f)
(rf 'read 1)   ;; => (#t #t #t #f #f #f #f #f)
```

Four registers, each 8 bits. Read by index, write by index. That is
essentially what a CPU register file looks like from the outside.
Chapter 12 wires one of these into a tiny CPU.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- A flip-flop stores one bit.
- A register is a bank of flip-flops, sampled together on the clock.
- A counter is a register that increments each tick.
- The program counter is a counter that can also be loaded.
- The register file is a small addressable bank of registers.
- All of this runs on the same substrate as chapter 5: Boolean gates
  with feedback.

Once you have registers and a clock, you have a **timeline**. Once you
have a timeline, the machine can plan. It can hold intermediate results.
It can execute one instruction after another.

Chapter 10 gives that timeline a name: state machines. Chapter 12 wraps
it all into a CPU.

## The loop appears

The counter is a loop made of hardware. The program counter is a loop
made of hardware. The clock itself is a loop — a signal that oscillates
high-low-high-low forever. Loops inside loops inside loops. And every
one of them is a place where a wire ate its own tail (chapter 8's
feedback) plus a rule for what to do next.

## Next

Chapter 10: state machines. Mealy and Moore. We name the timeline and
give it grammar.
")
